This book is called Reverse\nEffect, which was really
about-- it was time to\ncome out with some policy
discussions that were going\non in Chicago about whether
or not to clean wastewater\nbefore it was entered back
into the river system.
There is a lot of different\nproblems with the Chicago River
system, and so our\nwork in the book
was to try to explain\nthose, because it's
somewhat complicated.
There's very poor water quality.
There's a lot of flooded\nbasements because
of the hydrology system.
There's the threat of invasive\ncarp coming up the Mississippi
River, threatening to\nenter into the Great Lakes.
And then there's a lot\nof post-industrial fabric
along the river, which\nis of great potential.
About 100 years ago\nthese canals were built.
And this is what reversing\nthe Chicago River refers to.
The red lines are\ncanals that basically
took the water from emptying\nfrom the lake into the rivers,
and did the reverse.
Made the-- [chuckles] The\nrivers were going into the lake,
and now the lake\ngoes into the rivers
and ultimately across this\nsub-continental divide, joining
up with the Des Plaines\nRiver and ultimately
the Mississippi River, ending\nup in the Gulf of Mexico.
And that was in order\nto preserve the drinking
water that was getting polluted\nfrom all of these dumping
into the rivers.
That solution, of course, 100\nyears ago was a fine solution.
But today we know\nthat that's just
delaying the pollution\nto downstream
and messing up someone\nelse's water system.
So we wanted to\nexplain that part
and to also ask people how they\nwere using the river today.
So a real integral\npart of our practice
has become working with\ncommunity members, people,
individuals, the public, and\nreally speaking with them
and finding out their\nideas and attitudes,
more like an industrial\ndesigner would
do for a problem than\ntypically an architect.
But I think it should change.
I think architects and urban\ndesigners and landscape
architects should all\nbe very well-connected
