Finally, just a couple\nof the more urban scale
projects we've been focusing on\nover the last about six years.
And we've even started an urban\npractice within the office.
But it's based on connecting\nurban design and architecture,
so it really always has this\narchitectural scale to it
as well.
So Polis Station\nis a project that
was, again, self-initiated.
It was a reaction\nto what's going
on in the country\nbetween police--
the violence between police\nand community members.
And it was something\nthat-- at the time
we were designing a fire station\nin Brownsville and Brooklyn,
and we noticed that with\nfire stations or fire rescue,
people really like the\nfire rescue workers.
And they actually-- it is kind\nof like a welcoming place.
So we started to wonder, if the\npolice station could possibly
be improved would that help with\nthese difficult relationships?
In Chicago, about\n20 years ago, they
built all these prototype\npolice stations.
And, you know, even\nthough they're modern,
they never really asked anyone\nin the communities what they
wanted in their police station.
They're all identical\nand kind of plopped
on the different sites.
And so we were wondering, if\nwe could look at the history
and ask people about what they\nwanted in a police station,
what would they come up with.
If you look at the history\nof the police stations--
and this is kind of focusing\non the Northeast, I guess--
from Chicago to the\nNortheast-- they were once
not even buildings at all.
They were like little warming\nstations that people would use.
And these were community\nmembers who would just
walk around the\nneighborhood and make sure
that everything was safe.
So they actually came\nfrom the community.
And so what's changed is\nthat the car is introduced.
The police station has become\nsurrounded by parking lots.
So there are even--
this is in Chicago.
They're even more separated\nfrom the community.
And the police don't live there.
In fact, they're not\nlike the communities
that they're policing.
And there's a big, huge distrust\nbetween these two groups.
And so we thought of\ntaking this example, which
is in North Lawndale in Chicago,\nthe 10th district police
department--
I also taught a studio where\nwe looked at the situation
in New York.
But here these gigantic parking\nlots and hugely-wide roads--
130-foot wide-- are working\nto separate the community
from the police station.
And actually people are scared\nto go anywhere near the police
station because they're\nafraid to be injured and shot,
but also afraid to even\ngo in and report a crime.
And so it's really\ndysfunctional in a major way.
So we were able to gather some\ncommunity members from North
Lawndale, and police, and we did\na meeting with the two groups
together.
And we didn't work for\neither one of them.
And we asked them how to\nimprove the police station so
that there would be more trust.
And a lot of this was based\non the recommendations
from the Obama\nAdministration that
came out with a community\npolicing report.
And the things that they came\nup with were really cool.
Like, you know shared--
these would all be on the\npublic side of the station.
Shared compute resources,\nfree Wi-Fi, cafes,
even a barbershop.
The barbershop I like the\nbest, because that would be--
you know, you're basically\ntrying to build connections
between the two\ngroups and have them--
so when police\nare in the street,
they recognize people and\nthey don't just assume--
or, they treat them like people.
And there would\nbe conversations,
and there would be less\nconfrontational interactions.
So the idea that this would\nopen up on the public side
and really be part of\na community center.
What's really cool is\nthat this project--
people have called me from\naround the country that
are implementing these\nthings in police stations
around the country,\nwhich is really exciting.
In ours we raised enough money\nto put these sports courts
on the parking lot and take\naway some of the parking.
That was one of the things\nthat both the police
and the community\nmembers wanted.
But there was some fear about\ngoing near the police station.
But we went back a year\nlater and interviewed people,
and the parents were\nsaying that they really
felt that their kids were safer\nnow playing outside the police
station.
And so I think there's\na very small step,
but there's something in that,\nand that we were you know
showed images of how\nthis thing could really
start to take shape.
And we want to see\nthat advance further.
So finally, last thing\nis just a project
that's in progress right\nnow on the urban scale.
It's the Memphis\nRiverfront Concept Plan.
Memphis is a city on\nthe Mississippi River,
